        	<div class="header">
 
  <h2 style="text-align:center;">$\sum_{k=2}^n {n!\over (n-k)!(k-2)!}=n(n-1)2^{n-2}$</h2>

</div>

				
    		</div><!-- /.blurb -->
		</div><!-- /.container -->
		
	
  
	


	<p><b>Proof</b></p>
<p><br />
	
 
$$\sum_{k=2}^n {n!\over (n-k)!(k-2)!}$$
</br>
Note that $${{n}\choose{k}}={n!\over (n-r)!r!}$$
</br>
Also, we have $${{n-2}\choose{k-2}}=\frac{(n-2)!}{(n-2-k+2)!(k-2)!}=\frac{(n-2)!}{(n-k)!(k-2)!}$$
</br>
Inside the summation sign, we have the expression $${n!\over (n-k)!(k-2)!}$$ so it can rewritten as $$n(n-1){{n-2}\choose{k-2}}$$
</br>
Therefore $$\sum_{k=2}^n {n!\over (n-k)!(k-2)!}=\sum_{k=2}^n n(n-1){{n-2}\choose{k-2}}$$ 
</br>


We can rewrite as $$\sum_{k=0}^{n-2} n(n-1){{n-2}\choose{k}}$$
</br>
How we did it? In earlier expression $k$ ranged from $2$ to $n$, so $k-2$ ranged from $0$ to $n-2$. So we can take modify the original expression and consider $k$ varying from $0$ to $n-2$
</br>
Recall $$(1+x)^n={{n}\choose{0}}+{{n}\choose{1}}x+ {{n}\choose{2}}x^2+\dots {{n}\choose{n}}x^n=\sum_{k=0}^{n}{{n}\choose{k}}x^k$$
</br>
Put $x=1$,we get $$2^n=\sum_{k=0}^{n}{{n}\choose{k}}$$
</br>
Using the above result, we conclude that $$\sum_{k=2}^n {n!\over (n-k)!(k-2)!}=\sum_{k=0}^{n-2} n(n-1){{n-2}\choose{k-2}}$$ evaluates to $$n(n-1)2^{n-2}$$
	</br>
<br>
	
  
